node.text: Porsche is in the minds of many the ultimate sports car brand. Its cars – especially its legendary 911 – blend high performance with quality construction and even a solid reputation for dependability. But the brand that made its name with small nimble two-door sports cars ruffled feathers in the automotive world when it tried its hand at a four-door sport utility vehicle, the Cayenne. Today, SUVs make up a huge chunk of Porsche’s sales. The brand is now entering the race toward electrification – but this time the innovator is playing catch-up to others.

node.title: How Porsche went from sports cars to SUVs ... and EVs

node.text: It’s taken over two years, but these days Jeremy Mateo is finally feeling at home. Mateo, 27, is a real estate broker in Honolulu, Hawaii, and bought his first condo on Oahu island right before the coronavirus pandemic in March 2020. Over the course of a year he saved $60,000 for a down payment and worked toward his goal of buying his “dream home.” Then he spent another year renovating and furnishing his place. The last of his furniture arrived in spring 2021, finally closing the chapter on his homebuying journey. Here’s how Mateo bought his one-bedroom condo for $560,000. (With @CNBCMakeIt)

node.text: Violence and mass shootings erupted over the weekend, and could continue. 274 mass shootings have occurred this year, with 304 dead, which is on pace for one of the most violent years in history. Here's what the country's outlook is.

node.title: Violence and mass shootings erupted over the weekend

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 16, 2021. May be an image of monument, outdoors and text that says 'Economic "nirvana" should usher in roaring '20s, market bull predicts CNBC'.

node.text:
Ed Yardeni believes the U.S. economy is on the cusp of “nirvana.”⁠
⁠
Despite uncertainty surrounding inflation and Covid-19 variants, the longtime bull believes the pandemic is significantly accelerating corporate America’s adoption of cutting-edge technology designed to expand productivity.⁠
⁠
According to Yardeni, the move is ushering in a modern roaring ’20s on Wall Street.⁠
⁠
What kind of stocks does Yardeni say you should buy? Link in bio to find out.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 16, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Michael Burry of "The Big Shot" reveals a bet against Cathie Wood's ARK Innovation ETF TI B SH TRADE Heir CNBC'.

node.text:
New for subscribers: “The Big Short” investor Michael Burry is betting against Cathie Woods’ ARK Innovation ETF, according to a regulatory filing that revealed a short position via options. 👀⁠
⁠
Burry’s Scion Asset Management bought 2,355 put contracts against the red-hot tech ETF during the second quarter and held them through the end of the quarter. Investors profit from puts when the underlying securities fall in prices.⁠
⁠
How has the ETF performed so far this year? Link in bio. (Check out CNBC Pro for 7 day for free!)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 16, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Crypto market tops $2 trillion for the first time in nearly 3 months as bitcoin rallies CNBC'.

node.text:
Bitcoin topped $48,000 over the weekend, its highest level since May, but pared some of those gains on Monday.⁠
⁠
On Saturday, the digital coin hit $48,126.47, according to Coindesk data. (Around 9 a.m. ET on Monday, bitcoin was trading at $47,263.35.) Bitcoin’s rise lifted the value of the entire cryptocurrency market above $2 trillion on Saturday for the first time since mid-May, according to data from CoinMarketCap.⁠
⁠
What does one expert say investors should expect from bitcoin in the coming months? Link in bio.

node.text: The world was shocked this week by horrifying scenes of Afghans swarming the tarmac at Kabul’s international airport, grasping at their last chance to escape a country now overrun by the Taliban. 🔗 in today’s Story to read about how Afghanistan fell to the Taliban so quickly.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 16, 2021. May be an image of one or more people, people standing, outdoors and text that says 'Chaotic scenes at Kabul airport as Afghans and foreign nationals flee Taliban 10 CNBC'.

node.text:
Thousands of Afghans gathered on the tarmac at Kabul’s international airport in the hours after the Taliban captured the capital.⁠
⁠
The chaotic scenes show a desperate rush to escape the country.⁠
⁠
“If you don’t have a visa or passport, which the majority of Afghans don’t, you’re not going,” an analyst stuck in the country said.⁠
⁠
Read more at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 15, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Dogecoin is the "strongest" cryptocurrency as a medium of exchange, Mark Cuban says CNBC'.

node.text:
Though dogecoin was created as a joke and its creators never intended for it to be taken seriously, Mark Cuban says it has a unique use case over other cryptocurrencies.⁠
⁠
“It’s a medium that can be used for the acquisition of goods and services,” Cuban tells @CNBCMakeIt. “The community for doge is the strongest when it comes to using it as a medium of exchange.”⁠
⁠
What does Cuban think the future holds for other cryptocurrencies like bitcoin and ethereum? Link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 15, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says '1 in 3 people say return-to-office office negatively impacted their mental health CNBC'.

node.text:
Roughly 1 in 3 workers back in the workplace said the return-to-office shift negatively impacted their mental health, according to a June McKinsey survey.⁠
⁠
Workers who experienced declines in their mental health were five times more likely to report taking on reduced responsibility at work. Meanwhile, another 1 in 3 workers said going back to an office had a positive impact on their mental health, with the primary benefit being they feel more engaged upon their return.⁠
⁠
What could help reduce worker stress? Find out at the link in bio. (With @CNBCMakeIt)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 15, 2021. May be an image of tree, outdoors and text that says 'Treehouses are getting booked by wealthy travelers- and the photos show why WO CNBC'.

node.text:
Travelers looking for a vacation in the great outdoors are turning to a nostalgic source of comfort and solitude: treehouses. 🌲⁠
⁠
But these aren’t the treehouses of their childhood. Like the travelers who are booking them, the treehouses have matured too. Modern treehouses are more luxury homes than kid hangouts — with a price to match. Treehouses constructed by professionals can easily cost six figures to build.⁠
⁠
Check out photos of these insanely cool treehouses at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 15, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Anothe Another 3.9 million people quit their jobs in June and many are getting higher-paying roles CNBC'.

node.text:
The U.S. quitting spree is still going strong. 💪⁠
⁠
After dipping slightly in May, the share of people leaving their employer rose again in June, when another 3.9 million people quit their jobs, according to the latest Job Openings and Labor Turnover Survey. Meanwhile, opportunities continue to abound for job-seekers. Many employers are having to compete for workers by offering attractive signing bonuses, higher pay, better benefits and more accommodating work schedules.⁠
⁠
Details on how much wage growth job-switchers saw in the last year compared to all workers at the link in bio.⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 14, 2021. May be an image of 2 people and text that says 'Former FBI agent of 21 years: These are the 8 biggest warning signs that reveal a dishonest person CNBC'.

node.text:
Every person has a tell. ⁠
⁠
Your friends, co-workers, family members, partner and boss may actually be revealing their true intentions, but shrouding them in clever disguises.⁠
⁠
Robin Dreeke, a retired FBI special agent and former chief of the Counterintelligence Behavioral Analysis Program, spent 21 years defeating people whose sole intention was deception and trickery. Through years of trial and error, he recognized certain key patterns and learned how to "size people up" — or predict what others will do, and trust them accordingly.⁠
⁠
Visit the link in bio for the biggest warning signs that reveal a dishonest person. 🕵️ (With @CNBCMakeIt)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 14, 2021. May be an image of 2 people, people standing and text that says '240 minutes a day separates the rich from everyone else, says author who studies millionaires CNBC'.

node.text:
There are 1,440 minutes in each day. That is the one common denominator we all share. With respect to time, we are all on equal footing. And most people, rich or poor, use about 1,200 of those minutes for the following activities: work, commuting, family-related, sleeping, eating, bathing, bathroom, grooming and dressing.⁠
⁠
That leaves about 240 minutes of time each day. And it is what the rich do with those 240 minutes that separates them from everyone else.⁠
⁠
What do they do with those minutes? Find out at the link in bio. (With @CNBCMakeIt)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on August 14, 2021. May be an image of car, road and text that says 'Audi unveils the Skysphere: A futuristic, sinister-looking EV roadster concept car 00 AA R CNBC'.

node.text:
Audi’s newest concept car is a sleek, sinister-looking electric convertible called Skysphere that blends Batmobile-like technologies and aggressive design characteristics with luxury amenities.⁠
⁠
Audi executives said this week that the vehicle is essentially “two vehicles in one.” The first is an aggressive-driving roadster capable of reaching 60 mph in about four seconds and offers about 553 pound feet of torque. The second is a grand touring coach car that will drive itself and expand about 10 inches for a larger, more comfortable cabin.⁠
⁠
What's most notable about the concept car? Find out at the link in bio. (PS: You can check out more photos of the Skysphere in the article. 👀)
